lations":null,"definition":{"source":"wiktextract","senses":[{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to tuck up, to raise"},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to tuck up, to raise","examples":[{"text":"شَمَّرَ عَنْ سَاقَيْهِ","english":"to flee"},{"text":"شَمَّرَ عَنْ سَاعِدِ الجِدِّ","english":"to roll up one's sleeves"}]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"verbal noun of شَمَرَ (šamara) (form I)","tags":["form-of","noun-from-verb"]},{"pos":"adj","gloss":"light, agile, active, swift","tags":["rare"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"fennel (Foeniculum gen.)","tags":["rare"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"dill (Anethum graveolens)","tags":["rare"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"the Arabic tribe of Shammar","tags":["rare"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"ellipsis of إِمَارَةُ جَبَلِ شَمَّرَ (ʔimāratu jabali šammara, “Emirate of Jabal Shammar, a state derived from the tribe”)","tags":["abbreviation","alt-of","ellipsis","rare"]}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"From Aramaic, where attested forms include Jewish Babylonian Aramaic סִמְרָא, סִימְרָא (simrā), absolute state סְמַר (smar), Jewish Palestinian Aramaic שומרא (šummārā), Classical Syriac ܫܲܡܵܪܵܐ (šammārā) and ܫܘܼܡܵܪܵܐ (šummārā), all meaning fennel, deriving from Akkadian 𒌑𒄩 (šimru, simru, “fennel”), also found in Hebrew שֻׁמָּר (šummā́r, “fennel”) and שָׁמִיר (šāmī́r, “dill”), and likely Ugaritic 𐎘𐎎𐎗 (ṯmr, “likely fennel”). Related to Old Armenian շամրայ (šamray), շումրայ (šumray), a Semitic borrowing.\n\nFrom Old South Arabian 𐩦𐩣𐩧 (s²mr), occurring already BCE, in the earliest Middle Sabaean inscriptions."},"ipa":["/ʃam.mar/"]}